Partners















Lacy I. Rice
Managing Partner
Lacy Rice manages the company’s for-sale and for-rent residential acquisitions. Mr. Rice has 29 years of experience in real estate investment and corporate finance and serves on FCP's Investment Committee.
Prior to founding FCP, Mr. Rice was a Principal at The Carlyle Group. He served on the company’s real estate fund's Investment Committee. Prior to Carlyle, Mr. Rice worked at companies including Alex Brown, Haas & Haynie Corporation and Chemical Bank. Mr. Rice serves on the board of The Boys and Girls Clubs of Greater Washington. He received his MBA from Harvard Business School and BA from Princeton University.



Alex J. Marshall
Managing Partner
Alex Marshall is a 19-year veteran of the real estate industry, with specialized experience in financing, acquisitions and the repositioning of multi-family properties. Mr. Marshall is a member of the company’s Investment Committee and is responsible for the company’s multifamily acquisitions.  
Prior to joining FCP, Mr. Marshall was a member of the Real Estate Group at JPMorgan Partners and before that worked as an Associate in the Acquisitions Group at ING Clarion. He holds a BS in Finance from Boston College's Carroll School of Management.


Esko I. Korhonen
Managing Partner

 
Esko Korhonen has company responsibilities in commercial investment, capital markets and fund raising. He has more than 33 years of experience in real estate investment and development and serves on the Investment and Executive Committees for FCP.  Prior to founding FCP, Mr. Korhonen was a Principal of The Carlyle Group where he served on the company’s real estate fund's Investment Committee.  Before joining Carlyle, Mr. Korhonen was Vice President of ING Group, where he was responsible for ING's North American real estate portfolio. He began his real estate career with the Trammell Crow Company. Mr. Korhonen has served on the Board of Directors of Tower Realty Trust, Inc. (NYSE-TOW), the Board of Trustees of The Maret School in Washington, DC, Founding Member and Advisor for Fair Chance Fund, and currently is Co-Chair of The Northwestern University Leadership Council, Washington, DC, Regional Board Member of the Northwestern University Campaign Committee and a Trustee of the MD-DC chapter of The Nature Conservancy. Mr. Korhonen is a member of the Pension Real Estate Association, Urban Land Institute and District of Columbia Building Industry Association. He received his MBA from the J.L. Kellogg Graduate School of Business at Northwestern University and BA from Colgate University.


Thomas A. Carr
Managing Partner
Thomas A. Carr joined FCP in 2007, is a member of the company’s Investment Committee and has responsibility for commercial office investments, capital raising and general management. Mr. Carr has more than 36 years of experience in the real estate industry focusing on all aspects of development, operations, capital markets and investments.
Mr. Carr is the former Chairman and CEO of CarrAmerica Realty Corporation (formerly NYSE:CRE). He serves as Trustee and Past Chairman of the Board of the NHP Foundation and is on the Board of The Oliver Carr Company. He is a former member of the Executive Committee of the Board of the National Association of Real Estate Investment Trusts, a former member of the Real Estate Roundtable,  former President of the Board of The Maret School, and former Trustee of The Federal City Council. Mr. Carr has an MBA from Harvard Business School and a BA in Urban Studies from Brown University.


Lacy I. Rice
Managing Partner
Lacy Rice manages the company’s for-sale and for-rent residential acquisitions. Mr. Rice has 29 years of experience in real estate investment and corporate finance and serves on FCP's Investment Committee.
Prior to founding FCP, Mr. Rice was a Principal at The Carlyle Group. He served on the company’s real estate fund's Investment Committee. Prior to Carlyle, Mr. Rice worked at companies including Alex Brown, Haas & Haynie Corporation and Chemical Bank. Mr. Rice serves on the board of The Boys and Girls Clubs of Greater Washington. He received his MBA from Harvard Business School and BA from Princeton University.







5425 Wisconsin Avenue, Suite 202  | Chevy Chase, MD 20815 (240) 395-2000


 


FEP Capital Budgets


















Home
Login



Questions? Contact:
	Ana Ramirez
anar@rice.edu
	713-348-5343
	





Welcome!
Welcome to the FY 2018 electronic Annual Capital Budget process. Ana Ramirez, Director for Project Management and Pat Dwyer, Executive Director for Space Management will meet with school and division department heads to discuss potential projects and to review the format for submitting Facility Budget Requests (FBRs) to those new to the campus and new to the process.
To get started, just login with your NetID and password.
Any suggestions for improvement are welcome for future revisions of the web site.

Intro
Traditionally there have been many more annual capital budget requests than could be supported from available university funds.  As a result, only the top priority requests from each school and division are investigated and priced.  The Budget Committee closely scrutinizes the highest priority items.  Therefore, actively screen all potential projects and forward only the top candidates in priority order.
The expectation that a 15% funding contribution be made for each project from each school and division will continue this year.  Please designate the fund/org for local contributions for the Funding Source as requested on the request template.  The capital budget list is limited to projects that exceed $50,000.


FY 2018 CAPITAL BUDGET PLANNING SCHEDULE




Date
Activity


September 7, 2016
Kick-off letter to campus announcing start of FY 2018 Capital Budget process.


September 7 - September 30, 2016
Project development meetings scheduled with each school and division, as necessary, to discuss project(s) likely to be requested; identify major planning issues.


September 30, 2016
Deadline for all FBRs.


October 3 - October 7, 2016
Compilation of list and follow-up questions to requestors.


October 10 - December 2, 2016
Facilities Engineering & Planning/ Project Management and Engineering staff work with designated client representatives to define scopes of work and establish cost estimate(s). NOTE: Deadline for all requests is December 2, 2016.


Week of October 24, 2016
First review of capital project requests (Provost, VPA, VPF, FE&P).


Week of December 5, 2016
FE&P distributes documentation on cost estimates for academic requests and Deans meet individually with Provost to discuss requests. Site visits for proposed requests scheduled with the Provost, if necessary. Vice President for Administration is briefed on all non-academic requests.


December, 2016
As necessary, update project scope and pricing changes from Provost review.


January, 2017
Review Committee in-depth review of capital project requests.


February, 2017
Recommended list finalized and shared with schools and divisions.


March, 2017
Presentation of the FY 2018 annual capital budget to the Building and Grounds Committee. The B&G recommends approval of the annual capital budget by the Board of Trustees at the March Board meeting.


March/May, 2017
Communicate results of Board action.






Format for Requests
Please submit requests using the Annual Capital Budget Web-site. The deadline to submit requests is Friday, September 30, 2016.
Request Template: The request template has been formatted to summarize important information on potential projects. Potential projects are evaluated on such factors as cost, benefit, alternative solutions and the consequences of not doing the project. Tool tips have been included in the request template to assist in identifying this additional information.
Estimates: Facilities Engineering and Planning (FE&P) staff will work with designated contacts to confirm requirements and to develop cost estimates.
Meetings: Ana Ramirez and Pat Dwyer will meet with school and division department heads to discuss potential projects and to answer any questions about the FBR submittal process. Rene Salinas (Extension #5121; lrs5@rice.edu) will be calling to arrange these meetings to take place sometime during the month of September. If it is not necessary to meet, please contact Ana Ramirez.





		Annual Capital Budget Review Process
	









Facilities Engineering and Planning6100 Main MS-312, Houston, Texas 77005-1827       Mailing Address: P.O. Box 1892, Houston, Texas 77251-1892

